Step one: 
I decided to go with the structure below
ArbitrageBot/
├── src/
│   ├── ArbitrageBot.Domain/
│   ├── ArbitrageBot.Infrastructure/
│   ├── ArbitrageBot.Application/
│   └── ArbitrageBot.Api/
├── tests/
│   ├── ArbitrageBot.Domain.Tests/
│   ├── ArbitrageBot.Application.Tests/
│   └── ArbitrageBot.Integration.Tests/
└── ArbitrageBot.sln

Domain:
 this will be the innermost layer.
 it will have no dependencies on anything external
 not even nuggets or any framework beyond the basic class library
 the models will be in here (arbitrage opportunities, token pair, arbitrage leg), 
 it will also contain interfaces, domain logic, state transition

Application:
  this is where all uses cases will live... the scanner, analyzer, and executor logic stays here
  it will depend on the domain but then it wont know how any of those interfaces are implemented, 
  this makes easier for testing and also allows us to swap out implementations if we want to change how we do something without affecting the domain logic

Infrastructure:
 this is where we will implement the interfaces defined in the domain layer, 
 this is where we will have our implementations for interacting with the blockchain, 
 this is where we will have our implementations for interacting with the exchanges, 
 this is where we will have our implementations for interacting with any external services we need
 keeping it isolated means nethereum breaking changes can never reach the domain logic

Api: 
    this is where we will have our web api, 
    this is where we will have our controllers, 
    this is where we will have our dtos, 
    this is where we will have our mappings, 
    this is where we will have our dependency injection configuration  